{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528280"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:40:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14282"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14282"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.09,0.48,0.11,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6977"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107068"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6977"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89532"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1475"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16395"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34644"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107068"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 34-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-month history of itchy, red eyes. She reports a burning sensation in both eyes, and flakes around her eyes worse in the mornings. She feels that her cheeks are more flushed-looking despite no change in her cosmetic routine.  She has recurrent herpes simplex virus -1 oral infections and uses topical acyclovir for this.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Examination of her eyes reveals redness along the eyelid margins bilaterally, with some scaling visible at the base of the eyelashes. The conjunctiva appears slightly injected bilaterally. There is no corneal involvement noted.  Visual acuity is 6/6 bilaterally.  There is telangiectasia over both cheeks with a few pustules.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bacterial conjunctivitis","Dry eye syndrome","Blepharitis","Allergic conjunctivitis","Herpes simplex keratitis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eblepharitis\u003C/strong\u003E, a chronic inflammatory condition of the eyelid margins. The patient\u0027s symptoms of itchy, red eyes, gritty sensation, and crusting along the eyelashes are classic features of blepharitis. The examination findings of redness along the eyelid margins and scaling at the base of the eyelashes further support this diagnosis. Posterior blepharitis is related to a dysfunction of the meibomian glands and may also present with frothy discharge fom the eyelid margins. This is associated with rosacea which is suggested in this case by the reddened cheeks and pustules. Anterior blepharitis is caused by inflammation of the anterior eyelid margin however anterior and posterior blepharitis often present similarly and together.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment typically includes lid hygiene measures daily such as warm compresses and gentle cleansing of the eyelid margins. In some cases, chloramphenicol 1% eye ointment may be prescribed to treat the inflammation from anterior blepharitis if not controlled by lid hygiene alone. Posterior blepharitis may require oral antibiotics (doxycycline) if also not controlled by lid hygiene alone. The associated cause such as rosacea, dry eyes, acne or seborrhoeic dermatitis, should be addressed for long-term management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic conjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bilateral itching, tearing, and conjunctival injection. While some of these symptoms overlap with blepharitis, allergic conjunctivitis usually does not cause crusting along the eyelashes or significant eyelid margin involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial conjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E usually has a more acute onset and is characterized by mucopurulent discharge rather than the crusting seen in this case. The chronic nature of the symptoms (one month) makes bacterial conjunctivitis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDry eye syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a gritty sensation and redness, but it typically does not cause significant eyelid margin inflammation or crusting, nor be associated with rosacea. However as above, dry eye and blepharitis often coexist and can exacerbate each other.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex keratitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with unilateral symptoms and often includes corneal involvement, which is not noted in this case. It is often related to herpes simple virus-1 infections. The absence of vesicular lesions makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blepharitis is characterised by inflammation of the eyelid margins, often presenting with redness, itching, and crusting.","Blepharitis is often a chronic condition that requires ongoing daily lid hygiene"],"references":["Wong K. Blepharitis. Dermnet NZ. 2009.  Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/blepharitis","Geng R, Slomovic J, Bourkas A, Slomovic A, Sibbald R. Ocular rosacea: The often-overlooked component of rosacea.  JEADV. 2024. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/jvc2.428?af=R"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89532"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14282"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89532"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-25T00:26:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-25T00:26:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6977"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107068"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"descr